-- Spanish Stocks: ACS, Repsol, Reyal Urbis Shares Move in Madrid Trading
-- B y   M a n u e l   B a i g o r r i
-- 2010-12-29T16:58:55Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-29/spanish-stocks-acs-repsol-reyal-urbis-shares-move-in-madrid.html
Spain’s  IBEX 35 Index  rose for a
second day, adding 78, or 0.8 percent, to 9,981.5 at the 5:30
p.m. close in Madrid. The  Madrid Stock Exchange General Index 
advanced 0.7 percent to 1,015.29.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
Spanish market. Symbols are in parentheses after company names.  Actividades de Construccion y Servicios SA  (ACS SM) climbed
for a second day, gaining 1.5 percent to 35.60 euros. Spain’s
largest builder holds 29.4 percent of the voting rights in
Hochtief AG, according to the website set up by ACS to inform on
the progress of the offer.  Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria SA  (BBVA SM) rose 0.7
percent to 7.66 euros, snapping four days of losses.
Inveravante, the investment firm of Spanish billionaire Manuel
Jove, boosted its stake in BBVA to 5.067 percent after the last
share sale that Spain’s second biggest lender carried out,
Expansion reported, without citing anyone.  Gamesa Corporacion Tecnologica SA  (GAM SM) increased 2.8
percent to 5.85 euros, the biggest gain in the IBEX 35 Index
today. Iberdrola SA increased its stake in Gamesa to 19.077
percent, according to a regulatory filing.  NH Hoteles SA  (NHH SM) rose 2.5 percent to 3.45 euros, the
highest price since Nov. 19. Spain’s largest business hotelier
said in a filing it won a waiver from lenders on complying with
two agreed financial ratios in 2010 for a syndicated loan it
signed in 2007.  Obrascon Huarte Lain SA  (OHL SM) advanced 1.2 percent to
22.81 euros, extending yesterday’s gain. The Spanish
construction company agreed to continue talks with PBG SA over
buying Hydrobudowa Polska SA and Aprivia SA for a price of about
127 million euros ($167 million), it said in a filing today.  Repsol YPF SA  (REP SM) advanced 1.4 percent to 21.07 euros,
extending yesterday’s increase. China Petroleum & Chemical Corp.
completed its $7.11 billion purchase of a 40 percent stake in
Repsol’s Brazilian unit, as the Spanish oil company raised funds
to develop offshore projects.  To contact the reporter on this story:
